<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 92 / Pastoral sympathy persists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY ONE in three people would like to move to the countryside, rejecting
city life as dirty and stressful.
The possibility of a migration into rural Britain is highlighted in a Mintel
survey examining social and economic differences across regional divides. It
says 17 per cent of those under 35 in the top socio-economic groups (ABC1)
plan to move to rural areas in the next five years.
Greater London and south-east England experienced a net loss of 83,000
people in 1989 while Wales, south-west England and Scotland registered net
gains of 41,000. Net losses of more than 500,000 are forecast for London and
the south-east by the turn of the century.
Mintel questioned 1,000 adults on a range of socio-economic issues. The
survey's other findings include:
Northerners are the most avid bargain-hunters, searching for sales and
special offers. They are less likely to shop at a single supermarket,
whereas southerners prefer one-stop shopping.
Do-it-yourself enthusiasts are most common in Yorkshire and north-east
England.
Non-package overseas holidays, independently booked, are most popular with
southerners. Yorkshire and north-east holidaymakers are more likely to
return to familiar spots.
Regional Lifestyles, 1992. Mintel, 18-19 Long Lane, London EC1A 9HE. Pounds
795.
