<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 92 / Pound's fall gives industry scant aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE devaluation of sterling has given only a slight boost to manufacturers,
according to the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply. It says the
outlook for the sector remains gloomy.
According to its monthly poll of purchasing managers in manufacturing, new
orders last month showed little increase on September.
The pessimistic tone is echoed in a broader assessment of the economy by
Oxford Economic Forecasting, a consultancy, which says prospects for growth
have worsened.
Oxford Economic Forecasting said gross domestic product was likely to grow
by only 0.8 per cent next year after a fall of 0.9 per cent this year.
In the manufacturing sector, according to the institute's survey, sentiment
remains depressed, even though an 'activity index' based on the results
showed a slight rise.
The index, built up from an average of variables in the poll including
intentions about increasing output and hiring or sacking people, stood last
month at 47.7, up from 45.1 in September. Consumers last month registered a
rise in intentions to purchase goods and services over the next six months,
according to Verdict Research, a consultancy specialising in retailing. It
says the rise may be linked to seasonal changes ahead of Christmas.
Kwik Save, the discount grocery chain, has become the third most popular
food retailer after J. Sainsbury and Tesco, according to Audits of Great
Britain, the research company. It was in fifth place 20 months ago.
Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply, Easton House, Easton on the
Hill, Stamford, Lincs. PE9 3NZ. Free. UK Economic Prospects, November 1992.
Oxford Economic Forecasting, Templeton College, Kennington, Oxford, OX1 5NY.
