<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 92 / 'Men's club' still proves exclusive: The difficulties women
face in reaching the top in management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR MRS Sara Morrison, a long-standing board member of General Electric
Company and one of the participants in the Institute of Management survey on
female managers published today, advance notice of the report's findings
have made depressing reading.
'I'm surprised so many of the old barriers still loom so large,' she says,
referring to the main conclusion that the single biggest obstacle seen by
women to female progress at work was the continued existence of the 'men's
club' network. Prejudice by colleagues was the second most commonly
experienced barrier.
The results do not match her personal experience, she says, expressing her
astonishment that many of the attitudes described in the report had not died
out in the 1950s. 'But it's jolly difficult to argue against the findings,
given the number of people in the survey,' she says. The fact that 51 per
cent of the nation's brainpower is not being properly exploited is bad news
for women, but 'much more serious, it's bad news for UK Limited'.
Later this month, Opportunity 2000, the employer-led initiative that covers
more than 20 per cent of the workforce, will report on its first year of
operation. It will be interesting to note whether organisations have made
any headway in the past 12 months in tackling fundamental prejudices, or
whether they have stuck principally to improving the more obvious practical
conditions surrounding, for example, career breaks and part-time working in
junior grades.
There is a danger, the institute points out, that 'focusing on tangible ways
of allowing women to combine a family with a traditional management role
obscures the real debate'. It adds: 'If creche facilities and flexible
working are the whole answer, why do so many women still fall behind their
male counterparts at the early stages of a management career - even before
they have family responsibilities?'
Prejudice among colleagues is not restricted to men, the report discloses.
While 18 per cent of men in the survey said they would, or did, find it
difficult to work for a woman, 12 per cent of women made the same
confession. Only two thirds of women felt they received adequate respect
from male superiors, and the figure remained well under three quarters even
when it came to getting respect from female superiors. Some women observed
what has sometimes been described as the 'queen bee' syndrome. Said one:
'Women who make it to the top do not help or mentor others to do likewise.'
For one senior woman in the City, Ms Anne McMeehan, managing director of
Framlington Unit Management, respect is gained, regardless of sex, if
'you're clearly good at your job, provided you're not dealing with blinkered
or bigoted individuals'. Does she ever come across such individuals? 'Yes,
but of both sexes,' she says.
Women could also be their own worst enemies because they often undervalue
themselves, according to Ms Kathleen Wood, headteacher of Pimlico
Comprehensive School, London and a participant in the survey.
'At interviews you still do see women who feel the need to justify their
ability to run a home and a career,' she says. They emphasise that they have
the agreement of their partners in applying for the job. 'You wouldn't hear
men say that,' she says. By endlessly justifying themselves, such women end
up 'raising doubts in people's minds'.
Perhaps the most thought-provoking of the report's findings is that female
managers are significantly less likely than their male counterparts to be
married or have children and are more likely to be divorced. Ninety-two per
cent of the men in the sample were married while 32 per cent of the women
were unmarried. The reasons for the findings were not explored in the
questionnaire. It is possible, the report observes, that some women had made
a deliberate choice at an early stage, and that that choice had in itself
made it easier for them to follow a management career. It is also possible
that, faced with the practical difficulties of combining the two, many have
elected for a career over children. The institute says: 'If the choice is a
deliberate one for many, the findings seem to show that in the current
cor-porate climate women are justified in making it if they do want to reach
the top. Of the women managers who have had children, half say that caring
has adversely affected their career. Similarly, 39 per cent of those who had
taken a break to care for children had returned to work at a lower level.'
However, the report concludes that a deliberate choice of career or family -
a dilemma not presented to men - 'is not a realistic or sustainable solution
for the majority of women looking for a career in management'.
The Key to the Men's Club. Institute of Management Books, Burston
Distribution Services, Unit 2A, Newbridge Trading Estate, Newbridge Close,
Bristol BS4 4AX. Pounds 15 for IM members, Pounds 30 for non-members.
