<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 92 / Three copier suppliers face suspension of credit licences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Fair Trading will this week be asked to revoke the consumer
credit licences of three companies offering controversial 'copy plan'
schemes to users of office photocopier machines. Similar action is expected
against other companies.
The use of copy plans, under which the capital cost of photocopying
equipment is merged with the running costs to produce a charge-per-copy
agreement, is coming under increasing scrutiny following customer complaints
about alleged misrepresentation.
Customers allege that high-pressure sales techniques have misled them into
signing contracts with a life well in excess of that of the equipment and
which conceal several onerous and unfair conditions.
Some of the leasing companies offering copy plans are owned by leading banks
and institutions. which could be embarrassed if the activities of any of
their subsidiary operations were subject to OFT action.
On Wednesday, members of the Campaign to Clean Up Copier Contracts, and Mr
Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, will tell the OFT that
sufficient evidence has been assembled to justify the withdrawal of consumer
credit licences from three companies. They will also offer to compile
evidence of alleged contract abuse against several other leasing
specialists.
The campaign, started earlier this year by companies claiming to have been
misled into signing expensive copy plan agreements, says it has received
nearly 2,300 complaints. It is demanding a two-week cooling-off period to
enable customers to cancel agreements, and wants changes in the law to
extend to companies and other organisations the same protection available to
individuals under the consumer credit acts.
A campaign spokesman said yesterday: 'The photocopier industry is trying to
suggest that the abuses surrounding copy plan contracts have been stamped
out. Our evidence suggests the contrary and we will keep up pressure to
ensure malpractice is identified and stopped.'
The OFT, which is discussing the copy plan with the Department of Trade and
Industry, has warned that it will revoke the consumer credit licences of
photocopier leasing companies if contract malpractice is confirmed.
