<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 92 / Countdown starts for 10 mines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL has formally served notice to miners' union representatives
that it is starting a 90-day statutory consultation period, at the end of
which it intends to close 10 pits.
Letters inviting local union representatives to meetings with management
were issued yesterday as British Coal ceased production at two more pits -
Grimethorpe and Houghton Main in South Yorkshire - leaving only one of the
10 - Betws in south Wales - still cutting coal. British Coal officials said
the consultative period would present miners with an opportunity to argue
their case against closures.
Instead, miners' unions are concentrating their efforts on legal action to
force British Coal to resume production at all the pits. They also want the
10 pits to be discussed at national level and to be included in the
government's wide-ranging consultations on its energy policy.
Applications for injunctions by the National Union of Mineworkers, the
Nacods pit supervisors' union, and the Union of Democratic Mineworkers are
scheduled to be heard in the High Court on Tuesday.
The unions claim to have compiled evidence pointing to a deterioration of
coal faces, roadway and equipment at some of the pits that have ceased
production over the past two weeks. According to union officials, the
evidence suggests that British Coal is effectively pre-empting the outcome
of the consultation period by allowing the mines to become unworkable.
Yesterday a group of women demonstrators chanted and cheered as miners
emerged, possibly for the last time, from Grimethorpe Colliery.
Meanwhile, the Labour party will today launch a campaign aimed at exploiting
public outrage at the government's pit closures in an attempt to promote its
alternative economic strategy.
The effort to link the closure of the pits with wider fears of depression
and redundancies begins in earnest next week when Mr John Smith, the party
leader, begins a tour of mines in Durham and South Yorkshire.
Nottinghamshire County Council is to hold an independent inquiry chaired by
Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, last year's chairman of the Bar Council, into pit
closures and their effect on the local economy.
Evidence provided by the inquiry will be collated and presented to the
review promised by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
</TEXT>
