<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 92 / French fume over smoking curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE, a country renowned for its smoke-filled bars, Gauloises and
pipe-chewing detectives, will severely restrict smoking in public from
tomorrow.
Smokers will be allowed to light up only in areas expressly set aside for
them - at present, smoking is allowed everywhere except where expressly
forbidden. Individual offenders will face fines of up to FFr1,300 (Pounds
155), rising to FFr6,000 for restaurants or companies that fail to provide
proper ventilation or to set smokers well apart.
Similar measures have been proposed by the Italian cabinet presided over by
Mr Giuliano Amato, an acknowledged smoker, and will be considered by
parliament.
Why is France doing this to itself? Some 40 per cent of the adult population
of France smokes, more than in most European countries, and France even
invented the word nicotine. Jean Nicot, a 16th century diplomat, introduced
tobacco to Catherine de Medicis, French queen at the time, as a cure for
migraine.
A survey to be published in today's Le Parisien newspaper said 71 per cent
of adults polled intended to abide by the law. Some 27 per cent said they
may break it.
Everybody knows the ban is unworkable outside areas such as government
offices, airlines and railways - where the cleaners on the Paris Metro sweep
up three tonnes of cigarette-ends a day.
The restaurant trade is a bastion of resistance. It has asked for a two-year
grace period while its members find the money to install smoke extractors -
indicating a measure of compliance - but few are prepared to insult their
smoking clients.
'If one of my guests calls the police, it's quite simple - I will pay the
fine in the place of the smoker and let him go,' promises Mr Alain
Dutournier, proprietor of the celebrated Carre des Feuillants in central
Paris. 'It is a smokescreen, an idiotic law,' fumes Mr Joel Robuchon, owner
of the Jamin, another top Paris restaurant. 'Some of my clients have said
that if they can no longer smoke cigars, they will no longer come.'
The Patronat employers' organisation says the ban is socially divisive,
because privileged people with private offices - not public places - can
smoke as much as they like, while those who work in open-plan offices will
have to go to a special smokers' area.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
