<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 92 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Tax on life policies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I UNDERSTAND that life policies retained by the original policyholder to
maturity are exempt from CGT by virtue of the Taxation of Chargeable Gains
Act 1992.
However, on the recent maturity of two Scottish Widows life policies taken
out by me in 1969 and 1972, the company issued to me copies of a certificate
of chargeable event which they had sent to the Inland Revenue, showing an
amount of chargeable gain in each case. Does the issue of such a certificate
mean that they are chargeable to CGT?
The two policies were paid up by me in 1977. Would this make them liable to
CGT.
The gains shown on the certificates are chargeable to income tax, not CGT,
under sections 547 and 550 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988.
However, the rate of tax cannot exceed 15 per cent; it may effectively be 12
1/2 per cent (on part or all of the gains) if you were born before April 6
1927. If the gains plus the rest of your income of 1991-92 do not take you
beyond the basic rate limit (and you were born after April 5 1927), there
will be no tax to pay on the gains themselves.
It was the fact that you made the policies paid-up within their first ten
years which brought the maturity proceeds into the income tax net, in
accordance with the rules now reenacted in section 540(1)(b)(i) of the
Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988.
Furthermore, although the gains do not attract CGT in themselves, their
existence could increase the potential CGT Liability on any chargeable gains
in excess of the exempt amount (Pounds ,5500), but we gather that you did
not in fact have any gains liable to CGT in 1991-92.
This reply was given by Barry Stillerman of Stoy Hayward
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
