<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 92 / Tory motion placates rebels: Ashdown recommends support as
government woos Euro-sceptics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday averted a confrontation with its own backbenchers
by tabling a motion for Wednesday's Maastricht debate aimed at bringing Tory
Euro-sceptics back to the loyalist fold.
The move switched the political spotlight to the opposition parties amid
reports that the Liberal Democrats were under fierce pressure from Labour
and several of their own MPs to oppose the government.
Late last night Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, acted to end
speculation over his party's stance by announcing that he would be
recommending support for the government to his parliamentary colleagues.
'The Liberal Democrats will vote in favour of Britain's future in Europe,'
he said.
However, Mr Ashdown's position is likely to come under fire at the party's
Scottish conference today when delegates will debate an emergency motion
urging the party to take any action necessary to bring down Mr John Major's
government.
Labour is also attempting to bring the maximum pressure to bear on the
Liberal Democrats, warning that their credibility as an opposition party
will be in tatters if they are seen to shore up Mr Major when he is
critically vulnerable.
The nationalist parties and the Ulster unionists have yet to state their
positions, though most are expected to oppose the government.
The government's motion, which avoids any use of the word Maastricht, is
clearly intended to maximise the difficulties for Labour. It also makes it
extremely hard for the 20 Liberal Democrat MPs to justify opposing Mr Major.
Far from confronting the Conservative rebels, as had been widely expected,
the wording emerges as a highly defensive case for resuming treaty
ratification in parliament.
The text reminds MPs that a 244 majority in May committed the Commons to
proceed to the committee stage of the bill. It stresses Denmark's
clarification of its intentions and progress on defining 'subsidiarity'.
The motion underlines the importance of a 'leading role' for the UK in
enlarging the Community and using membership to develop jobs and investment.
It ends with an invitation to the government to proceed with the bill in
order to 'consider its provisions in further detail'.
The initial response of several Conservative Euro-sceptics was extremely
cautious. While some diehards, such as Mr Richard Shepherd and Mrs Teresa
Gorman, remain determined to vote against the government, other opponents of
the treaty, such as Mr William Cash, were reserving their position last
night.
Their final stance looks likely to be settled at a meeting on Tuesday
evening when they will attempt to agree a common approach. Speculation is
mounting that they may opt to abstain rather than oppose the motion.
Labour dismissed the motion as chiefly aimed at persuading the maximum
number of Liberal Democrat MPs to back Mr John Major and 'save his bacon'.
A senior Labour official said an amendment would be tabled next week with
wording intended to appeal to Tory Euro-sceptics by putting back the
committee stage until after the Edinburgh summit.
At the same time, it would underline Labour's own argument that the debate
constitutes a confidence vote in Mr Major and the government.
Labour MPs are doggedly backing their leadership's line of outright
opposition. But their stance provoked an attack from Mr Michael Heseltine,
the trade and industry secretary, who accused Mr John Smith of abandoning
his principles and emulating Harold (now Lord) Wilson.
'We have a sort of Harold Smith in charge of the Labour party,' he told a
BBC radio interviewer.
Speaking in his Huntingdon constituency, Mr Major commended the motion as
ensuring that Britain did not isolate itself from the European mainstream.
He said that the Euro-sceptics 'don't represent the majority of the
Conservative party and they don't represent the maj-ority of the people of
this country'.
Tory party officials are confident of winning the vote next week, but Mr
Major plans to continue his battle for hearts and minds of backbenchers with
further meetings.
