<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / EC VAT transition plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The EC Commission is to try to simplify the transitional system for
collecting and accounting for value added tax and excise duties in the
single European market, writes Andrew Hill in Brussels.
The system, which comes into force from next January 1, is designed to adapt
current VAT procedures to the abolition of border controls. It has been
widely criticised for imposing new administrative burdens on European
business.
But Mrs Christiane Scrivener, EC tax commissioner, said yesterday Brussels
would publish a new directive aimed at eliminating certain technical
difficulties with the system. The directive will tackle VAT problems which
might arise from 'triangular trade' in the EC. For example, a Belgian
company ordering Spanish goods for delivery to a French subsidiary will not
have to register for VAT in France. Instead the French subsidiary will be
directly liable. The transitional system should be replaced with a
definitive scheme from January 1997.
</TEXT>
